body:
E.g. select the gallery example, select 'Card' and request a code completion

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2978182/21188899/bf9d6c5e-c214-11e6-8396-02ccb012e697.png)

It should jump to 'Card' being selected from the list so I can look at the documentation. I don't understand why 'Expando' is the first item, and the out one out of alphabetical order.

comment_data.body:
I believe `Expando` is the first in the list because you previously selected it using code completion somewhere else. At the top of the list there are the most frequently used items, then others go alpha-sorted.

`Card` is not focused in the completion list because caret is before `Card` word in the code. So there's no prefix to match. If you put caret after `Card` then the focused item will be different.

BTW to see documentation you can press F1 without invoking code completion at all.

So far I do not see any bugs to fix.
cc @sethladd for his thoughts, I know that he has been interested in improving the code completion UX recently

> At the top of the list there are the most frequently used items, then others go alpha-sorted.

That's very good to know. That helps explain a lot :)

One more hint. Items sorting in the completion has 2 modes: lexicographical and relevance. The current mode is shown in the bottom-right corner of the popup (Greek 'Pi' or Latin 'A'). You can switch mode by clicking it. In lexicographical mode IDE simply does alpha-sort, it doesn't respect priority given by the Analysis Server or frequency of the previous usages.

As for focusing the item that matches text written AFTER caret: this decision is neither in scope of Flutter nor Dart plugin. You may file a request to change IntelliJ IDEA's core completion engine. Though core guys may have their own opinion on the problem.

> cc @sethladd for his thoughts, I know that he has been interested in improving the code completion UX recently

Luke, FYI we are working on a larger initiative to improve editing in Q1; there is a raw list of candidates here: https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/labels/topic-editing

> E.g. select the gallery example, select 'Card' and request a code completion

@lukechurch, I am curious, how did you end up with the caret right before `Card` as part of selecting it? I experimented a bit myself and whether I used the mouse of keyboard I could not come up with a way where it did not end up either in the word or right after it -- and in all those cases, completion does the right thing.

@alexander-doroshko actually one case seems odd: if you double click `Card` the editor selects it and places the caret right after the word. If you then invoke complete, it ignores the `Card` prefix and thus behaves differently than when you place the caret right after `Card` with the keyboard. Why is that?

Interesting :). I never noticed it during 13 years of coding in IntelliJ IDEA. Probably I never mixed selection and completion, I can't think out a real use case that would lead me to this situation.

Though I thought a bit and found this behavior reasonable. Picking an item from the completion list is an editor action similar to typing a word. When you have any selection and start typing - selection is removed and substituted with what you type. And the same happens when you pick an item from the completion list: if there is any selection - it is substituted with the picked item. That's why it makes no sense to check prefix matching when the prefix is selected - it will be overwritten anyway. I believe it is done by design.
